rid of the keyword</span><span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"182.04\">and just uses a pair of square brackets.</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"186.03\">That\'s exactly the same as in JavaScript.</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"190.01\">So if we save that, we are still using print_r.</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"193.09\">If we refresh the page in the browser,</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"196.03\">we get exactly the same result.</span>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"198.07\">So using the shorthand works exactly the same</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"202\">as using the traditional method with the array keyword.</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"205.06\">It doesn\'t matter which you use,</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"207.02\">it\'s very often just a matter of personal preference.</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"210.03\">I like to use the shorthand.</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"213.01\">You can add more elements to an existing array</span> <span class=\"transcript ga\" data-ga-action=\"click\" data-ga-label=\"toc-video-transcript\" data-duration=\"216\"